import pandas as pd
from glob import glob
import os
class DataMerger:
    def __init__(self, file_pattern):
        self.file_pattern = file_pattern
        self.dfs = []

    def read_and_pivot(self, file_path):
        df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
        short_df = df.pivot(index='timestamp', columns='short_name', values='price')
        short_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
        self.dfs.append(short_df)

    def merge_data(self):
        merged_df = pd.concat(self.dfs, ignore_index=True)
        merged_df.sort_values(by='timestamp', inplace=True)
        merged_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
        merged_df.set_index('timestamp', inplace=True)  # Set 'timestamp' as the index
        return merged_df

    def process_files(self):
        file_paths = sorted(glob(self.file_pattern))
        for file_path in file_paths:
            self.read_and_pivot(file_path)
        final_df=self.merge_data()
        final_df.index = pd.to_datetime(final_df.index)
        return final_df

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

class TimeSeriesPlotter:
    def __init__(self, dataframe):
        self.dataframe = dataframe

    def plot_all_time_series(self):
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        for column in self.dataframe.columns:
            plt.plot(self.dataframe.index, self.dataframe[column], label=column)

        plt.title('Time Series Data')
        plt.xlabel('Time')
        plt.ylabel('Values')
        plt.legend(fontsize='small')
        plt.show()

    def plot_single_time_series(self):
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        for column in self.dataframe.columns:
            plt.plot(self.dataframe.index, self.dataframe[column], label=column)
            plt.title(f'Time Series Data for {column}')
            plt.xlabel('Time')
            plt.ylabel('Values')
            plt.legend(fontsize='small')  # Adjust the fontsize here
            plt.show()
plotter=TimeSeriesPlotter(data)

import seaborn as sns
class CorrelationHeatmapPlotter:
    def __init__(self, dataframe):
        self.dataframe = dataframe

    def plot_heatmap(self):
        # Calculate correlation matrix
        corr_matrix = self.dataframe.corr()

        # Set up the matplotlib figure
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

        # Create a heatmap using seaborn
        sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', linewidths=0.5)

        # Set the title
        plt.title('Correlation Heatmap')

        # Show the plot
        plt.show()

import numpy as np
class LogReturnsCalculator:
    def __init__(self, df, date_column='timestamp'):
        self.df = df
        self.date_column = date_column

    def calculate_log_returns(self):
        # Make sure the DataFrame is sorted by date
        self.df = self.df.sort_values(by=self.date_column)
        
        # Calculate log returns for each stock
        price_columns = self.df.columns[0:]  # Exclude the timestamp column
        for col in price_columns:
            self.df[f'{col}'] = self.df[col].pct_change().apply(lambda x: np.log(1 + x))
    
    def get_result(self):
        return self.df
proced=LogReturnsCalculator(data)
proced.calculate_log_returns()
log_df=proced.get_result()
log_df= log_df.drop(index=log_df.index[0])
log_df.tail()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

class DensityPlotter:
    def __init__(self, df):
        self.df = df

    def generate_density_plots(self):
        # Set the style for the plots
        sns.set(style="whitegrid")

        # Get the list of columns in the DataFrame
        columns = self.df.columns

        # Generate density plots for each column
        for col in columns:
            plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
            sns.histplot(self.df[col], kde=True, color='skyblue')
            plt.title(f'Density Plot for {col}')
            plt.xlabel(col)
            plt.ylabel('Density')
            plt.show()
plotter = DensityPlotter(log_df)
plotter.generate_density_plots()

import pandas as pd

class TimeSeriesStatistics:
    def __init__(self, dataframe):
        self.dataframe = dataframe

    def calculate_descriptive_stats(self):
        return self.dataframe.describe()

    def calculate_mean(self):
        return self.dataframe.mean()

    def calculate_median(self):
        return self.dataframe.median()

    def calculate_std_dev(self):
        return self.dataframe.std()

    def calculate_min(self):
        return self.dataframe.min()

    def calculate_max(self):
        return self.dataframe.max()

    def calculate_quantiles(self, quantiles_list):
        return self.dataframe.quantile(quantiles_list)

    def calculate_range(self):
        return self.dataframe.max() - self.dataframe.min()

    def calculate_skewness(self):
        return self.dataframe.skew()

    def calculate_kurtosis(self):
        return self.dataframe.kurt()

    def print_all_statistics(self):
        print("Descriptive Statistics:")
        print(self.calculate_descriptive_stats())
        print("\nMean Values:")
        print(self.calculate_mean())
        print("\nMedian Values:")
        print(self.calculate_median())
        print("\nStandard Deviation:")
        print(self.calculate_std_dev())
        print("\nMinimum Values:")
        print(self.calculate_min())
        print("\nMaximum Values:")
        print(self.calculate_max())
        print("\nQuantiles:")
        print(self.calculate_quantiles([0.25, 0.5, 0.75]))
        print("\nRange:")
        print(self.calculate_range())
        print("\nSkewness:")
        print(self.calculate_skewness())
        print("\nKurtosis:")
        print(self.calculate_kurtosis())
stat=TimeSeriesStatistics(log_df)
stat.print_all_statistics()

import pandas as pd
import scipy.stats as stats

import pandas as pd
import scipy.stats as stats

class DistributionAnalyzer:
    def __init__(self, df):
        self.df = df

    def determine_distributions(self, significance_level=0.05):
        columns = self.df.columns
        distribution_results = {}
        for col in columns:
            result = self._perform_anderson_darling_test(self.df[col])
            is_normal = result.statistic < result.critical_values[2]  # 2 corresponds to the 95% confidence level
            # Store the results in the dictionary
            distribution_results[col] = {
                'Distribution': 'Normal' if is_normal else 'Non-Normal',
                'Anderson-Darling Statistic': result.statistic,
                'Critical Values': result.critical_values,
                'Significance Level': significance_level
            }

        return distribution_results

    def _perform_anderson_darling_test(self, data):
        result = stats.anderson(data)

        return result

import pandas as pd
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

class UnitRootTester:
    def __init__(self, df):
        self.df = df

    def conduct_adf_test(self, significance_level=0.05):
        results = {}

        for col in self.df.columns:
            result = self._perform_adf_test(self.df[col])
            results[col] = {
                'ADF Statistic': result[0],
                'p-value': result[1],
                'Critical Values': result[4],
                'Is Stationary': result[1] < significance_level
            }

        return results
    def _perform_adf_test(self, data):
        result = adfuller(data)
        return result
#Tester and Results

#Form the output data
class HourlyToDailyConverter:
    def __init__(self, stock_data):
        self.stock_data = stock_data
        self.daily_data_list = []

    def preprocess_data(self):
        # Extract date and hour columns
        self.stock_data['date'] = self.stock_data.index.date
        self.stock_data['hour_of_day'] = self.stock_data.index.hour
    def convert_to_daily(self):
        # Filter hours between 8:00 and 18:00
        filtered_data = self.stock_data[(self.stock_data['hour_of_day'] >= 9) & (self.stock_data['hour_of_day'] <= 18)]

        # Get the unique column names excluding date and hour_of_day
        column_names = [col for col in self.stock_data.columns if col not in ['date', 'hour_of_day']]

        # Loop through each column and convert to daily
        for column_name in column_names:
            # Pivot the DataFrame with proper aggregation for each column
            daily_data = filtered_data.pivot_table(
                index='date', columns='hour_of_day', values=column_name, aggfunc='mean'
            )

            daily_data.index=pd.to_datetime(daily_data.index)
            # Store the result in the list
            daily_data=daily_data.ffill()
            self.daily_data_list.append(pd.DataFrame(daily_data))
        return self.daily_data_list
    def display_daily_data(self):
        # Display the resulting DataFrames in the list
        for column_name, daily_data in self.daily_data_list:
            print(f"\nDaily Data for {column_name}:\n{daily_data}")
converter = HourlyToDailyConverter(log_df)

import pandas as pd

class DataFrameShifter:
    def __init__(self, original_df,list_of_dfs):
        self.original_df = pd.DataFrame(original_df)
        self.list_of_dfs = list_of_dfs
        self.shifted_dfs = []

    def shift_and_concatenate(self, num_shifts_self, num_shifts_other, fill_value=None):
        for i in range(1, num_shifts_self + 1):
            shifted_df_self = self.original_df.shift(periods=i)
            shifted_df_self.columns = [f'{col}_shifted_self_{i}' for col in shifted_df_self.columns]
            self.shifted_dfs.append(shifted_df_self)

        # Shift for other DataFrames
        for idx, other_df in enumerate(self.list_of_dfs):
            for i in range(1, num_shifts_other + 1):
                shifted_df_other = other_df.shift(periods=i)
                shifted_df_other.columns = [f'{col}_shifted_other_{idx}_{i}' for col in shifted_df_other.columns]
                self.shifted_dfs.append(shifted_df_other)

        concatenated_df = pd.concat(self.shifted_dfs, axis=1)
        return concatenated_df

def process_list_of_dataframes(list_of_dfs, num_shifts_self=5, num_shifts_other=1, fill_value=None):
    processed_dfs = []

    for i,original_df in enumerate(list_of_dfs):
        other_dataframes = [df for j, df in enumerate(list_of_dfs) if i != j]
        
        shifter = DataFrameShifter(original_df, other_dataframes)
        processed_df = shifter.shift_and_concatenate(num_shifts_self=num_shifts_self, num_shifts_other=num_shifts_other, fill_value=fill_value)
        processed_df.index=pd.to_datetime(processed_df.index)
        processed_dfs.append(processed_df)

    return processed_dfs

input_data_list = process_list_of_dataframes(output_list, num_shifts_self=3, num_shifts_other=1, fill_value=None)

import pandas as pd
def process_dataframes(output_list, features_list):
    processed_output_list = []
    processed_features_list = []
    processed_raw_list=[]
    for idx in range(len(output_list)):
        output_df = output_list[idx]
        features_df = features_list[idx]
        raw_out_df=output_list_prices[idx]
        # Merge dataframes using index columns
        merged_df_1 = pd.merge(output_df, features_df, left_index=True, right_index=True, how='outer')
        merged_df = pd.merge(raw_out_df,merged_df_1, left_index=True, right_index=True, how='outer') 
        # Drop rows with NaN values
        merged_df = merged_df.dropna(axis=0, how='any')

        # Separate the first ten columns as output_df
        raw_out_processed = merged_df.iloc[:, 0:10]
        output_df_processed = merged_df.iloc[:, 10:20]
        # The remaining columns are features_df
        features_df_processed = merged_df.iloc[:, 20:]
        # Append processed dataframes to the lists
        processed_output_list.append(output_df_processed)
        processed_features_list.append(features_df_processed)
        processed_raw_list.append(raw_out_processed)
    return processed_raw_list,processed_output_list, processed_features_list
# Process the dataframes using the function

A custom made model that takes the average of support vector regression and Ridge regression was created

In [45]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, RegressorMixin
from sklearn.svm import SVR
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

class AverageEnsemble(BaseEstimator, RegressorMixin):
    def __init__(self, svr_params=None, ridge_params=None):
        """
        Initialize the AverageEnsemble.

        Parameters:
        - svr_params (dict): Parameters for SVR model.
        - ridge_params (dict): Parameters for Ridge model.
        """
        self.svr_params = svr_params if svr_params is not None else {}
        self.ridge_params = ridge_params if ridge_params is not None else {}
        self.svr_model = SVR(**self.svr_params)
        self.ridge_model = Ridge(**self.ridge_params)

    def fit(self, X, y):
        """
        Fit the SVR and Ridge models on the training data.

        Parameters:
        - X (array-like): Input data.
        - y (array-like): Target values.

        Returns:
        - self
        """
        self.svr_model.fit(X, y)
        self.ridge_model.fit(X, y)
        return self

    def predict(self, X):
        """
        Predict target values for input data.

        Parameters:
        - X (array-like): Input data.

        Returns:
        - array-like: Predicted target values.
        """
        svr_preds = self.svr_model.predict(X)
        ridge_preds = self.ridge_model.predict(X)
        average_preds = (svr_preds + ridge_preds) / 2.0
        return average_preds

# Set a seed for reproducibility

class CustomPipeline:
    def __init__(self, model):
        self.pipeline = Pipeline([
            ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
            ('model', model)
        ])

    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.pipeline.fit(X, y)
        return self

    def score(self, X, y):
        return self.pipeline.score(X, y)

    def predict(self, X):
        return self.pipeline.predict(X)

    def set_params(self, **params):
        self.pipeline.set_params(**params)
        return self

class CustomGridSearchCV:
    def __init__(self, pipeline, param_grid,cv, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error'):
        self.grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline.pipeline, param_grid=param_grid,cv=cv, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=1)

    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.grid_search.fit(X, y)
        return self

    @property
    def best_params_(self):
        return self.grid_search.best_params_

    @property
    def best_score_(self):
        return self.grid_search.best_score_

    def predict(self, X):
        return self.grid_search.predict(X)

import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import TimeSeriesSplit
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

def tscv_average_validation_error(y, n_splits=20):
    tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=n_splits,test_size=1)
    validation_errors = []

    for train_index, test_index in tscv.split(y):
        y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]

        # Use shifted input as prediction (using the last value of training set for each column)
        y_pred = np.tile(y_train[-1], (len(y_test), 1))-np.tile(y_train[-1], (len(y_test), 1))
        # Calculate the mean squared error for this fold for each column
        mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, multioutput='raw_values')
        validation_errors.append(mse)
    average_validation_error = np.mean(validation_errors, axis=0)
    return average_validation_error.mean()

def calculate_average_errors_for_list(y_list, n_splits=20):
    average_errors = []

    for y in y_list:
        # Assuming tscv_average_validation_error is defined as before
        avg_val_error = tscv_average_validation_error(y.values, n_splits)
        average_errors.append(avg_val_error)

    return average_errors

class DataFrameList:
    def __init__(self, dataframes):
        self.dataframes = dataframes

    def get_last_row_of_each_dataframe(self):
        last_rows = []
        for df in self.dataframes:
            if isinstance(df, pd.DataFrame) and not df.empty:
                last_row = df.tail(1)
                last_rows.append(last_row)
            else:
                # Handle cases where the object in the list is not a DataFrame or it's empty
                last_rows.append(None)
        return last_rows
